Although it’s late, I couldn’t let World Cancer Day go by without acknowledgement.
Though the years go by the memories stay vivid. 
Treatment lasted a year. 
Yet, cancer’s affects are everlasting. 
Childhood cancer research is still disgustingly underfunded. I still pray for a day that we see a treatment that is not so brutal that it’s after affects remind survivors daily of what they endured. 

Today we honor those we have lost, those still fighting, and the survivors 🎗️

#worldcancerday #ewingsarcoma

This weeks home football game theme is yellow out in support of pediatric cancer. Our Viking cheer team will be running a Miracle Minute to collect donations towards more research. Read more below to find out more about Claire!
Hi my name is Claire Russell, I am in eighth grade and i go to Aylen Junior High. When I was 4 years old, i had a bone cancer called Ewings Sarcoma. The month of September is known for being Childhood Cancer awarness month. Childhood cancer research only gets 4% of money donated towards research. So, I try my best to get more money donated, so that kids can have a childhood not spent in a hospital.

Today, 11/22, is International Ewing Sarcoma Awareness Day. Today I am both thankful to have survived, and remembering and honoring those we lost, and those still fighting. Why is today Ewing’s Sarcoma Day? From the National Institute of Health website - 

"The most common mutation that causes Ewing sarcoma involves two genes, the EWSR1 gene on chromosome 22 and the FLI1 gene on chromosome 11. A rearrangement (translocation) of genetic material between chromosomes 22 and 11, written as t(11;22), fuses part of the EWSR1 gene with part of the FLI1 gene, creating the EWSR1/FLI1 fusion gene. This mutation is acquired during a person's lifetime and is present only in tumor cells. This type of genetic change, called a somatic mutation, is not inherited.

The protein produced from the EWSR1/FLI1 fusion gene, called EWS/FLI, has functions of the protein products of both genes. The FLI protein, produced from the FLI1 gene, attaches (binds) to DNA and regulates an activity called transcription, which is the first step in the production of proteins from genes. The FLI protein controls the growth and development of some cell types by regulating the transcription of certain genes. The EWS protein, produced from the EWSR1 gene, also regulates transcription. The EWS/FLI protein has the DNA-binding function of the FLI protein as well as the transcription regulation function of the EWS protein. It is thought that the EWS/FLI protein turns the transcription of a variety of genes on and off abnormally. This dysregulation of transcription leads to uncontrolled growth and division (proliferation) and abnormal maturation and survival of cells, causing tumor development.

The EWSR1/FLI1 fusion gene occurs in approximately 85 percent of Ewing sarcomas. #ewingsarcoma
